# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-antiquarian-society
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] The **1767 Milestones** are historic milestones located along the route of the Upper Boston Post Road between the cities of Boston and Springfield in Massachusetts.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] The 40 surviving milestones were added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1971.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] Massachusetts has a total of 129 surviving milestones including those along the upper Post Road.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] The stones are so named, despite having been placed in many different years, because of a 1767 directive of the Province of Massachusetts Bay that such stones be placed along major roadways.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] The state highway department was directed in 1960 to undertake their preservation.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] Many of them underwent a major restoration in 2018.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] The first stone was erected by Paul Dudley, one of the prominent citizens of early 18th century Massachusetts, in Roxbury, which was at the time a separate community.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] Roxbury was located at the end of the Boston Neck, a narrow isthmus separating the mainland from the Shawmut Peninsula, where Boston was located.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] Travelers going by land from Boston to other areas had to travel over the neck and through Roxbury to reach their destinations.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] The Roxbury junction where Dudley placed the first stone was where several routes branched, heading south and west across New England.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] The stones that Dudley erected have the initials PD on them, usually at the bottom of the stone.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] The most chatty of these milestones (not part of this collection), is inscribed P Dudley rather than PD, and is located on the corner of Centre and South Streets in Jamaica Plain.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] The stones listed for miles 23 through 29 in Wayland and Sudbury are actually guideposts rather than milestones, and do not list any mileage.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] They were erected at road intersections rather than at the mile marks.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1767-milestones] The stones are quarried granite posts with plug & feather tool marks and post-date 1800.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] On Tuesday, June 9, 1953, a rare, violent and deadly tornado struck the city of Worcester, Massachusetts and surrounding areas.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] A total of 4,000 buildings were damaged or destroyed, and the National Weather Service estimated that 10,000 people were left homeless.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The tornado caused $52.193 million ($590 million in 2023 when adjusted for inflation) in damage, ranking it the costliest tornado recorded in its time.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] EDT, the tornado developed in a forest near the town of Petersham and moved through Barre, where two people were killed.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] It then moved through the western suburbs of Worcester, where 11 more people were killed.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The storm then passed through Worcester, destroying Assumption College and several other buildings, killing 60 people.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] After striking Worcester, it killed 21 more people in the towns of Shrewsbury, Southborough, and Westborough, before dissipating over Framingham.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] On June 7, 1953, a strong shortwave trough moved eastward over the Rocky Mountains, bringing with it strong upward motions that induced lee cyclogenesis: the formation of a low-pressure area over eastern Colorado.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The combination of the warm, unstable air in place over the Great Plains and an elevated mixed layer from the desert Southwest led to conditions favorable for severe thunderstorms and tornadoes.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] More than 30 tornadoes occurred that day across Colorado, Kansas, Nebraska, and Iowa, including a violent tornado that killed 11 people near Arcadia, Nebraska.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] On June 8, the storm system moved northeast.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] These conditions led to several tornadoes in the states of Michigan, Ohio, and Nebraska, most notably the Flint-Beecher tornado.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The storm killed 116 people in the northern Flint suburb of Beecher and injured 844.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] In addition, seven other tornadoes across the region caused 449 more injuries and 26 more fatalities.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] After the Fujita scale came into use, the Flint-Beecher tornado was rated F5.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] On the morning of June 9, the low-pressure system had moved northeastward into Ontario near the south end of Hudson Bay.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] An occluded front extended south from it, towards a triple point with a warm front and cold front near the northern end of Lake Superior.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The warm front extended southeast across New York, Pennsylvania, and New Jersey and moved northeast throughout the day, bringing warm, moist, and unstable air into the New England area.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] In the mid-atmosphere, the elevated mixed layer was still in place, keeping storms from forming earlier in the day before maximum temperatures were reached.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] By afternoon, temperatures in Worcester had reached 80 °F (27 °C), with a dew point of 66 °F (19 °C); in combination with cold air aloft, this meant atmospheric conditions were very unstable and conducive to severe weather.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Furthermore, amplified wind shear was present in the afternoon of June 9, making conditions in the atmosphere supportive of supercell development and tornado formation.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Forecasters at the National Weather Service office in Boston believed there was a possibility for tornado activity in the area; however, they did not include such an advisory in their forecast, fearing that people might panic unnecessarily.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Since 1953 was the first year tornado and severe thunderstorm warnings were used, forecasters compromised and issued the first severe thunderstorm watch in the history of Massachusetts.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Most news reports only mentioned possible thunderstorms.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] This caused the tornado to strike with very little warning to the residents.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The tornado first developed over the Quabbin Reservoir in Petersham, Massachusetts, at 4:25 p.m EDT.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] It was witnessed by boaters on the reservoir, who initially saw three funnels.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] After brushing Petersham (occasionally with twin funnels several hundred feet apart), the tornado tracked southeastwards and slammed into the rural towns of Barre and Rutland, with two fatalities occurring at each location.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The massive tornado tore directly through suburban Holden, completely wiping out the Brentwood Estates subdivision and resulting in multiple fatalities.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] At 5:08 p.m., the tornado entered Worcester and grew to a width of one mile (1.6 km).
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The damage was tremendous in Worcester, the second-largest city in Massachusetts, and some areas faced the worst damage compared to that from any other U.S. tornado.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Hardest-hit areas included Assumption College (now Quinsigamond Community College), where a priest and two nuns were killed.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The main building's three-foot (0.91 m) thick brick walls were reduced by three floors, and the landmark tower lost three stories.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] A nearby storage tank, weighing several tons, was lofted and tossed across a road by the tornado.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The nearby Burncoat Hill neighborhood saw heavy devastation (especially on its western slope), but it was the Uncatena-Great Brook Valley neighborhoods to the east of Burncoat Hill that were razed, with the tornado possibly reaching F5 intensity in this area.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Houses and rows of homes vanished, with the debris granulated and scattered well away from their foundations.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Forty people died in the Uncatena-Great Brook Valley areas alone.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] A 12-ton (10.89 metric-ton) bus was picked up, rolled over several times, and thrown against the newly constructed Curtis Apartments in Great Brook Valley, resulting in the deaths of two passengers.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The Curtis Apartments blueprints were blown all the way to Duxbury (near Plymouth), 75 miles (121 km) away.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Across Boylston St. from the Curtis Apartments, the Brookside Home Farm, a city-operated dairy facility and laundry, sustained total damage, with six men and the herd of 80 Holsteins killed.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Houses and bodies were blown into Lake Quinsigamond.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The six fatalities at Brookside were the most in any one building in the tornado's path.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] At approximately 5:20 p.m., the funnel moved into Shrewsbury and maintained its one-mile (1.6 km) width throughout much of the town, killing 12.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The tornado was still in full-force when it moved through downtown Westborough (five deaths), where it began curving towards the northeast in its final leg.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] In the storm's final moments, three people perished in the collapse of the Fayville Post Office in Southborough.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Coincidentally, around the time it ended at 5:45 p.m., a tornado warning was issued, albeit too late.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] A separate F3 tornado also struck about the same time the warning was issued in the nearby communities of Sutton, Northbridge, Mendon, Bellingham, Franklin, Wrentham and Mansfield in Massachusetts, injuring 17 persons.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Another tornado did minor damage and caused several injuries in Fremont and Exeter in Rockingham County, New Hampshire; other smaller tornadoes occurred in Colrain, Massachusetts, and Rollinsford, New Hampshire.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Baseball-size hail was reported in a score of communities affected by the Worcester supercell.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Airborne debris was strewn eastward, reaching the Blue Hill Meteorological Observatory 35 miles (56 km) away, and even out into Massachusetts Bay and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The farthest documented distance of tornado debris was an item that blew from Holden to Eastham on Cape Cod, a distance of 110 miles (180 km), one of the farthest from a U.S. tornado.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The Worcester and New England tornado outbreak led to major changes in how severe weather was monitored in the United States.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] In response to the storm, the Storm Prediction Center was reorganized on June 17, 1953, and efforts continued to develop a nationwide system of weather radar and trained storm spotters.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] After this tornado, the 2011 tornado in Joplin, Missouri, was the only tornado in the United States to cause more than 100 fatalities.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The strength of the Worcester tornado itself has been debated for decades.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Official records had classified it as an F4 tornado.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] However, damage observed in several communities, including Rutland, Holden, Worcester, Shrewsbury, and Westborough, appeared similar to damage typically associated with an F5 tornado.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Due to this disagreement, the National Weather Service convened a panel of experts in Spring of 2005 to review the available evidence.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The panel considered whether the tornado should be reclassified as F5 but decided in the summer of 2005 to retain the original F4 rating.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] The panel concluded that many of the destroyed homes could not be examined closely enough to determine how well they had been anchored.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Some buildings, particularly those built in the postwar period, may have been more vulnerable to extreme winds than older structures.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/1953-worcester-tornado] Without detailed engineering data, the panel determined it was not possible to reliably distinguish between F4 and F5 damage, since the visible effects would likely appear similar.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] The **2021–22 Saint Vincent Hospital strike** was a labor strike involving nurses at the Saint Vincent Hospital in Worcester, Massachusetts, United States.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] The strike began on March 8, 2021, following disputes between the Massachusetts Nurses Association, which represents about 800 nurses at the hospital, and the hospital regarding staffing levels, and ended on January 3, 2022, after the nurses ratified an agreement with the hospital.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] Saint Vincent Hospital is a hospital owned by Tenet Healthcare and located in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] It is one of the few for-profit hospitals in Massachusetts.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] Beginning around 2019, hospital officials and union representatives from the Massachusetts Nurses Association (MNA, a labor union which represents several hundred nurses at the hospital) began to negotiate issues regarding pay and staffing levels at the hospital.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] According to the hospital, a labor contract proposal between the two groups included a "substantial" pay increase for the nurses, but by 2021, the two groups had still not come to an agreement regarding staffing levels.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] The hospital claims that the union's demands are "unreasonable" and allege that the hospital has "one of the most generous staffing ratios in the state".
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] However, the union rejects this claim, arguing that nurses routinely have to attend to five patients at a time and that staffing levels at the nearby UMass Memorial Medical Center are lower than those at Saint Vincent.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] In both December 2020 and January 2021, some nurses performed informational picketing outside the hospital.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] In mid-February 2021, the nurses voted to authorize open-ended strike action against the hospital, and on February 23, the union issued their 10-day notice of their intent to strike.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] The vote had passed with 89% of the nurses voting to approve the strike action.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] The last strike action taken by the union was a 2017 strike at Tufts Medical Center that lasted one day and was followed by a four-day lockout, while the union's last open-ended strike (a strike with no set time limit) occurred at Brockton Hospital in 2001 and lasted 104 days.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] MNA members had previously performed strike action at Saint Vincent in 2001 while seeking their first labor contract with the hospital.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] The last meeting between the union and hospital representatives before the strike started was on March 3, where a counteroffer made by the union was rejected by the hospital without a subsequent counteroffer.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] On March 8, 2021, the strike began, with approximately 800 nurses performing a walkout.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] The strikers announced that they planned to picket from 6 a.m. to midnight until "we accomplish what we set out to do".
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] To accommodate for the nurses' absence, the hospital hired replacement workers at a cost of $5.4 million for five days.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] Several nurses crossed the picket line, though the union claimed it was fewer than they had anticipated.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] Representative Joe Kennedy III joined the picket line in support of the strikers, while U.S.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] Senator Elizabeth Warren and Representative Jim McGovern were at the picket line that afternoon.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] That same day, the strike became the longest nurses strike in the state in two decades.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] During the strike, the hospital has experienced issues with other unions representing hospital workers.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] Local 1445 of the United Food and Commercial Workers (UFCW) announced plans to perform informational picketing alongside the nurses, as their contract with the hospital had expired on February 28 without a replacement.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] Additionally, Local 170 of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters claimed that their members were being tasked with duties outside their normal work, a claim which has been denied by the hospital's CEO Carolyn Jackson.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] On March 15, the hospital alleged that union members were bullying and harassing nurses who had crossed the picket line and issued a list of incidents they claimed had been committed by striking nurses.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] The union denied the accusations and accused the hospital of deflecting from the issues that had caused the strike.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] On March 21, the strike entered its second week.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] On March 28, the *Telegram & Gazette* reported that the hospital had set up security cameras outside the hospital to monitor strikers, with Jackson claiming that they were to ensure the safety of people entering the hospital.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] The cameras were criticized by the union as an intimidation tactic and an unnecessary expenditure.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] In addition, the city council of Worcester approved a resolution stating their support for the strike, and Massachusetts Attorney General Maura Healey voiced her support.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] On March 29, *Spectrum News* reported that the hospital was spending about $30,000 per day on police details.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] Additionally, an April 2 article in *The Republican* claimed that the hospital had spent several million dollars over the first several weeks of the strikes on replacement nurses, with the average replacement nurse being paid double the average pay for a regular nurse at Saint Vincent.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] On April 4, an Easter event was held at the picket line.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] On December 17, 2021, over nine months after the strike had begun, the MNA and the hospital reached a tentative agreement to end the strike, pending ratification from the union nurses.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/2021-saint-vincent-hospital-strike] The vote to ratify the agreement took place on January 3, 2022, which the nurses voting overwhelmingly in favor of ratification, thus ending the strike after 301 days.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] The **Abbott Street School** is a historic school building at 36 Abbott Street in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] Built in 1894, it is a good local example of Romanesque Revival architecture.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] It served as a public school until 1981, after which it was converted to residential use.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] The building was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1980.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] The former Abbott Street School is located west of downtown Worcester, on the west side of Abbott Street between Pleasant and Chandler Streets.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] It is a 2-1/2 story brick building with a hip roof and Romanesque Revival styling.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] Its most prominent feature is a projecting central turret, topped by a conical roof.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] It has a dentillated cornice, and round-arch windows on the second floor of the turret.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] Windows have rusticated granite sills, and there is a wide stone water table between the basement and ground floors.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] The main entrances flank the turret on either side, projecting slightly from the main block and recessed under round-arch openings with a granite keystone.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] A two-story addition extends to the rear.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] The school was designed by Boston architect William Forbush and built in 1894.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] Stylistically it is similar to the 1891 Downing Street School, also designed by Forbush, but with less elaborate trim.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] In 1905-06 it was enlarged, with a sympathetic design by Worcester builder J.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abbott-street-school] The city operated the school until 1981, after which it was converted to residential use.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The school's namesake is Abby Kelley Foster, a noted 19th-century leader in abolitionist and women's rights movements who resided in Worcester.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] On February 25, 2003, the Board of Education voted unanimously to renew the school's 5-year charter.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] Theresa Andre is the first person to ever graduate from this school in 2006.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] Abby Kelley Foster started with Grades K-5 in a factory building.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The middle and high school programs came later and are located in adjacent buildings.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The Elementary (K–3), Middle (4–7) and High School (8–12) buildings.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] They are located next to Kendrick Field which provided them with a great place to have field days, but in the year 2009 they transformed the old building next to it (including a parking lot) into a new playground and 2 athletic fields.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] They made another old building into a full court gym for the Elementary and Middle Schools in 2008.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] Due to overcrowding, the school leased space at Temple Emanuel for grades 6-8 during the 2002–2003 school year.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The school board decided to build a new high school.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The building was bought from Norton Abrasives and was completely refurbished.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] During the construction of the school, students were temporarily put an old school building on Ararat Street.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The building opened for the 2009–2010 school year and is still currently functional.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The building was equipped with an auditorium, gymnasium (named James Walsh Gym after the head of the board of trustees), Cafeteria and Library.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] There was also the installation of a chemistry and biology lab plus a lecture hall.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] Adjacent to the auditorium and gym is a warehouse that the school uses for various storage and projects, such as the school play.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] More classrooms were built in the High school due to overcrowding during the 2016–2017 school year.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] They are now opened for the 2017–2018 school year.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] During the building of the new high school in 2009, the school also turned an old storage building and an old playground into a new playground.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The adjacent parking lots were also turned into one small athletic and one large mixed use field.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The playground and both fields are covered in Astro-turf.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] There was also one building located next to the small field that was turned into a full court gym and is used by the Elementary and Middle School.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] Abby Kelley Foster focuses on reading, writing, math and music as key subjects for elementary students to be expanded upon in each grade level.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The average student teacher ratio is 22:1.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The school also focuses on technology with curriculum beginning early with simple tasks progressing to the high school level with advanced topics on Microsoft Office, Adobe Photoshop and web design.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] For the 2010–11 school year the school was authorized to give International Baccalaureate diplomas to students who enroll in these excelled courses.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] These courses are offered to students of the Junior and Senior classes.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] As of 2007, Abby Kelley Foster shows mixed results in MCAS testing.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] Grade 3 tests show that 35% of students were proficient in English Language Arts arts while 17% of students were proficient in math.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] In 2004, Abbey Kelley Foster students scored 37% in English Language Arts and in 2006 (the year of last available data), scored 32% in math.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] This compares to state averages of 39% and 40%, respectively.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] In grades 4–8, math results remain below the state average.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The highest results come in grade 8 with 35% proficiency as compared to the state average of 45%.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] English Language Arts scores are higher, and in all but one case in grades 4–7 are above the state average.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] In science testing during grades 5 and 8, scores are 29% and 32% compared to the state averages of 41% and 35%, respectively.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] Grade 10 testing shows proficiency well below the state average at 43% for English Language Arts and 60% as compared to 71% and 69%, respectively.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] The MCAS STE test, which measures proficiency in biology, chemistry, introductory physics and technology/engineering was measured at Abby Kelley Foster in the 58% in biology and 37% in technology/engineering as compared to the state averages of 42% and 35%.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] According to the Massachusetts Department of Elementary & Secondary Education, both ninth and tenth graders take the test, which will become a graduation requirement in 2010.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] During the 2006–2007 school year, Abby Kelley Foster participated in the Advanced Placement program by offering courses in the following areas: Biology, Government & Politics, US History, and World History.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/abby-kelley-foster-charter-public-school] Students who do well on the final test in these subjects may be eligible for college credits.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] The **Adams Academy** was a school for boys in Quincy, Massachusetts founded by President John Adams, who outlined his wishes for a school to be built on the site of John Hancock's birthplace in an 1822 deed of trust.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] Opened in 1872, the Academy operated as a college preparatory school for just over three decades, ultimately closing in 1908.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] Today, the property is still owned by Adams's original trust, the Adams Temple and School Fund, and its landmark Ware and Van Brunt building has been leased to the Quincy Historical Society for several decades.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] President John Adams (1735-1826) was a native of the northern precinct of Braintree, Massachusetts, which later became the town of Quincy, Massachusetts.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] In 1822, Adams executed several deeds of trust to convey a portion of his estate assets to a trust, the **Adams Temple and School Fund**, with the Town of Quincy named as its fiduciary trustee.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] When a sufficient amount of financial capital was accumulated, Adams' instructions called firstly for the construction and furnishing of a congregational church, and secondly, for the founding of a Latin and Greek academy for boys and the construction of a suitable schoolhouse.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] Adams advised that both structures be built from local Quincy granite sourced from his quarry lands.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] Lemuel Bryant and members of the Quincy political family, including Colonel Josiah Quincy I and his son, revolutionary patriot and lawyer Josiah Quincy II.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] Adams's wish was for the church to be constructed first; the First Parish Church was completed in 1828, just two years after Adams's death.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] The school came significantly later — approximately fifty years after the founding of the Adams Fund, its board of supervisors hired the architects William Robert Ware and Henry Van Brunt to design the schoolhouse.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] Architectural plans were approved in 1869, and the firm of Messrs.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] Clement and Creasy was contracted for the school's construction.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] The Adams Academy building was finished in 1871 at a cost of $29,000.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] The Adams Academy opened its doors in 1872, and remained in operation until 1908.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] Its peak enrollment was 140 students during the 1876–77 school year.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] The Academy was modeled after its athletic rivals, Phillips Academy and Phillips Exeter Academy.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] Per Adams's wishes, the school curriculum strongly emphasized the study of the classics.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] Students were given an education that aimed to prepare them for matriculation at Harvard College.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] By the early twentieth century, however, enrollment was in decline, and the Adams Academy closed in 1908.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] After the Academy closed, the Adams Temple and School Fund sought other uses for the building that were in keeping with John Adams's original bequest.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] For many years, it was used by a variety of civic organizations, including the Boy Scouts, American Legion, and the Red Cross.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] In 1972, the building was leased to the Quincy Historical Society, which is now its tenant.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] The Society uses the building as a museum and library.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/adams-academy] The building was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1974, and designated a National Historic Landmark in 1994.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] The **Addison Prentiss House** is a historic house in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] 1877, and is one of the city's finer Gothic Revival houses built in brick.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1980.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] The Addison Prentiss House is located east of downtown Worcester, at the end of Channing Way, a stub street off Channing Street in the city's Bell Hill neighborhood.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] It is a 2+1⁄2-story brick building with an L-shaped configuration and gabled roof.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] It is oriented facing south toward Kendall Street.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] The main facade is dominated by a 3+1⁄2-story tower, and a porch that extends across the full width of the front.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] Other elevations are asymmetrical, with varying gables and porches.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] Windows are generally set in rectangular openings, with rustically cut granite sills and lintels.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] A wood frame porch extends across the northern facade, which appears to have served as the building's principal entry.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] Addison Prentiss, the first owner, was a printer, book dealer, and publisher.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] He came to the city about 1852, and is known for publishing one of the first bird's-eye views of the city in 1851.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] Charles Hanson, the next owner, is believed to be the city's first Swedish immigrant; he was a piano tuner who eventually opened a music shop downtown.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/addison-prentiss-house] Hanson was also active in civic affairs and organizations that aided further Swedish settlement.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] The **American Antiquarian Society** (**AAS**), located in Worcester, Massachusetts, is a learned society and a national research library of pre-twentieth-century American history and culture.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] Founded in 1812, it is the oldest historical society in the United States with a national focus.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] Its main building, known as Antiquarian Hall, is a U.S.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] National Historic Landmark in recognition of this legacy.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] The mission of the AAS is to collect, preserve and make available for study all printed records of what is now known as the United States of America.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] This includes materials from the first European settlement through the year 1900.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] The collections of the AAS contain over four million books, pamphlets, newspapers, periodicals, graphic arts materials and manuscripts.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] The Society is estimated to hold copies of two-thirds of the total books known to have been printed in what is now the United States from the establishment of the first press in 1640 through the year 1820; many of these volumes are exceedingly rare and a number of them are unique.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] Historic materials from all fifty U.S. states, most of Canada and the British West Indies are included in the AAS repository.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] An act of congress requires that one copy of the journals of the Senate and of the House of Representatives along with other documents are to be transmitted to the Governor of Massachusetts for the use and benefit of the Society.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] One of the more notable volumes held by the Society is a copy of the first book printed in America, the Bay Psalm Book.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] AAS has one of the largest collections of newspapers printed in America through 1876, with more than two million issues in its collection.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] On the initiative of Isaiah Thomas, the AAS was founded on October 24, 1812, through an act of the Massachusetts General Court.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] It was the third historical society established in America, and the first to be national in its scope.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] Isaiah Thomas started the collection with approximately 8,000 books from his personal library.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] The first library building was erected in 1820 in downtown Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] In 1853, the Society moved its collections to a larger building at the corner of Highland Street, also in Worcester.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] This building was later abandoned and another new building was constructed.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] Designed by Winslow, Bigelow & Wadsworth, the Georgian Revival building was completed in 1910 and stands on the corner of Park Avenue and Salisbury Street.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] There have been several additions to this building to accommodate the growing collection.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] The most recent addition was completed in 2019 and created room for an updated HVAC system, conservation lab, and multi-use learning lab.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] AAS was presented with the 2013 National Humanities Medal by President Obama in a ceremony at the White House.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] As part of AAS's mission as a learned society, it offers a variety of public lectures and seminars.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] One topic to which AAS dedicates significant academic energies is printing technology, especially in 18th century British North America.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] Since Isaiah Thomas was a newspaper man himself, he collected a large number of printed materials.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] With regard to printing, paper making, edition setting, and reprinting, not much had changed in European technology by the eighteenth century.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] It was not until the late eighteenth century that paper-making material began to evolve from a hand-woven cloth to an industrial pulp.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] AAS undertakes special efforts to preserve printed records from this time period, as the Society maintains an on-site conservation department with various sewing, cloth, and binding materials to aid in the preservation process.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] Over its two-hundred-year history, the Society has had 14 formal leaders who have shaped the organization's vision, collections, and day-to-day operations.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] Leadership roles at the AAS have historically overlapped in chronology, as different roles oversaw different aspects of the Society simultaneously.
[src:american-antiquarian-society/american-antiquarian-society] The American Antiquarian Society's membership includes scholars, writers, journalists, historians, artists, filmmakers, collectors, American presidents, and civic leaders.
